  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in
scalarizeInstruction() asserting that the inferred scalar type for a
VPReplicateRecipe equals the cloned IR instruction's type. For the reproduced
loop, the VPReplicateRecipe wraps a Select instruction whose original IR type is
i32, but VPTypeAnalysis inferred i16. This mismatch triggers the assertion.\n\n2.
Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe initial IR sequence: load i16 -> zext i16 to i32 -> and
i32 (.. & 15) -> select i32 -> trunc i32 -> store i16.\nThe printed Initial/Final
VPlan show the zext vanished and the and now operates directly on the load value:
WIDEN ir<%and> = and ir<%l>, ir<15>. Subsequently, the select recipe operands
became the i16 load-derived value and a constant 0 presumably also treated as i16
(after simplification), but the underlying select instruction still has i32 type
in IR.\nThus VPlan operands were rewritten to narrower types without adjusting
the underlying IR instruction/type. TypeAnalysis for VPReplicateRecipe::Select
infers the result type from operand VPValues (lines 225-230), caching i16,
conflicting with the IR select's i32 type used when cloning.\n\n3. Root Cause
Analysis:\nThe inconsistency arises because the VPReplicateRecipe for a Select
relies on operand-based inference (inferring from operands[1] and [2]) instead of
the authoritative underlying instruction's type. After transformations that
altered operand VPValues to narrower types (removing extends), the inference
produces a different type (i16) than the underlying instruction (i32). No
mechanism updates the underlying instruction or widens the operands back, leading
to mismatch at execution.\nHence, the design assumption that inferring from
operands is always consistent with underlying instruction breaks after certain
VPlanTransforms simplifications. The narrow fix is to derive (and enforce) the
select's type directly from the underlying IR instruction for VPReplicateRecipe,
similar to how casts, loads and allocas are handled.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Point(s):\nFile: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanAnalysis.cpp, lines 219-230
(the Select case inside VPTypeAnalysis::inferScalarTypeForRecipe for
VPReplicateRecipe).\nChange the Select handling from inferring via operands 1 and
2 to simply returning the underlying instruction's type. Optionally retain (under
NDEBUG) a consistency assert that operand types (if non-void) either match or can
be implicitly converted, but crucially do not override the underlying result
type.\nNew code sketch:\ncase Instruction::Select: {\n  return
R->getUnderlyingInstr()->getType();\n}\nRemove the ResTy inference & caching
based on operands for Select.\nThis ensures scalarizeInstruction sees matching
inferred type and IR type.\n\nRationale: Underlying IR instruction's type is the
source of truth; operand modifications during VPlanTransforms must not silently
change the recipe's defined type. Other opcode branches (casts, loads) already
return underlying type. This minimally invasive change fixes the assertion
without broad redesign.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy adjusting VPTypeAnalysis to return
the underlying IR select instruction's type for VPReplicateRecipe, we eliminate
the mismatch between inferred and actual cloned types, resolving the crash. The
change confines type authority to the IR instruction for Select, making VPlan
robust against operand simplifications that alter operand types. Further
follow-up could audit binary ops similarly, but current reproducer only requires
fixing Select handling.",
